Probably=C2=A0the story of meme stocks goes something like this:
=09Because of social media, retail investors are more able to coordinate wi=
th each other to all buy the same stock=C2=A0at the same time.=09Because it=
 is fun and occasionally lucrative, they do.=09Some structural feature of t=
he modern stock market gives them=C2=A0leverage. The story is not=C2=A0just=
 =E2=80=9Cwhen a lot of retail investors buy a stock at once, it goes up=E2=
=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cwhen a lot of retail investors buy a stock at=
 once,=C2=A0that causes big institutional traders to buy the stock too, so =
it goes up.=E2=80=9D

Steps 1 and 2 of that story are surely true, and=C2=A0possibly=C2=A0suffici=
ent to explain a lot of meme-stock activity.=C2=A0Step 3 is a bit murkier, =
and not absolutely necessary; it is imaginable that, if enough individuals =
on Reddit buy a stock, the stock will go up a lot. Still most people seem t=
o believe some form of Step 3. The=20
two main forms are:
=09The short squeeze: If a lot of retail investors buy a stock all at once,=
 its price will go up enough that hedge funds who had=C2=A0shorted=C2=A0the=
 stock will have to get out of their positions. Those hedge funds will=C2=
=A0also=C2=A0have to buy the stock, and then it will really go up a lot.=09=
The gamma squeeze: If a lot of retail investors buy=C2=A0call options=C2=A0=
on a stock at once, the options market makers who sell them the options wil=
l have to buy the underlying stock as a hedge for the call options they sol=
d. This will also push up the stock. And the market makers=E2=80=99 hedge i=
s=C2=A0dynamic, meaning that as the stock goes up they have to buy even mor=
e stock to remain properly hedged, in a virtuous cycle that further pushes =
up the stock.

This is not investment advice, and you should not believe these stories too=
=C2=A0literally; there are no perpetual-motion machines in finance. After t=
he 2021=C2=A0meme-stock mania, the US Securities and Exchange Commission=20
released a report finding some evidence of gamma squeezes and short squeeze=
s, but not really endorsing either theory. And, again, =E2=80=9Ceveryone bo=
ught the stock at once=E2=80=9D is at least a theoretically sufficient expl=
anation, without any of these technical factors.
You could also add a third form of retail leverage, which goes something li=
ke:
=09Everyone noticed, in 2021, that retail investors on Reddit could move st=
ocks. So they updated their models, in various ways, to reflect this. They =
started paying more attention to social media, trying to buy stocks that re=
tail investors were talking about. And if they were short sellers, they sta=
rted paying extra-close attention, so that they could=C2=A0immediately=C2=
=A0get out of any short positions that looked like they were becoming meme =
stocks. The result of this is that, as soon as retail investors start buyin=
g a meme stock, fast-money institutions =E2=80=94=C2=A0momentum-tracking he=
dge funds, social-media-tracking funds, factor-neutral funds, nervous short=
 sellers =E2=80=94=C2=A0will also start buying that stock, and it will go u=
p.

