Researchers haven=E2=80=99t nailed down precisely why more money is associa=
ted with more happiness.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right =
in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to =
Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks!
       =20
  [1] Of course the reverse is also possible. Musk *did* call for a =E2=80=
=9Cpause=E2=80=9D on AI development a year ago; possibly =E2=80=9CAI, but b=
ury it underground=E2=80=9D really is the best idea.


  [2] That is, $560 billion times 13% is less than $200 billion times 42%. =
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s RICH function tells me that Musk=E2=80=99s Tesla stake =
is worth a touch more than his SpaceX stake (and that the SpaceX stake is 4=
2%) but that depends on your valuation assumptions; SpaceX is not public.


  [3] Byrne Hobart calls it a =E2=80=9Cform of capital arbitrage=E2=80=9D: =
=E2=80=9CThe goal is to bet on whichever part of [the Musk] constellation w=
ill be sucking up resources from the other parts. =E2=80=A6 This is the rig=
ht way to think about the =E2=80=A6 valuation of Elon Musk's xAI. It's not =
the capitalized value of what the company has done so far, or even the valu=
e of Elon Musk's fame as a way to differentiate from other AI businesses. B=
ut it does make sense as a proxy for the net present value of Tesla, SpaceX=
, and Twitter talent that might be quietly repurposed to work on AI instead=
.=E2=80=9D


  [4] And been partially reversed: Tesla peaked in 2021, and has been below=
 the pay package's $650 billion valuation target since January.


