olor: #ccc;">what I would advise here</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Proxy-advisory firm Glass Lewis has advised Te=
sla shareholders to vote against Elon Musk=E2=80=99s multibillion-dollar pa=
y package at the company=E2=80=99s meeting next month.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a 71-page report, Glass Lewis told sharehol=
ders that Musk=E2=80=99s proposed compensation=E2=80=94recently valued at $=
46 billion=E2=80=94could dilute their existing holdings in Tesla. The packa=
ge would concentrate his ownership, making him the largest shareholder =E2=
=80=9Cby a healthy margin.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shareholders will vote at the June 13 meeting =
on Musk=E2=80=99s pay package and other proposals, including moving the com=
pany=E2=80=99s incorporation to Texas, which Glass Lewis also advised again=
st. Proxy advisers=E2=80=99 recommendations can influence shareholder votes=
, as institutional shareholders look to them for advice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk=E2=80=99s compensation was originally app=
roved by Tesla shareholders in 2018, but it was struck down by a Delaware c=
ourt in January because of concerns about the approval process. In the ruli=
ng, the judge cited Musk=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cextensive ties=E2=80=9D with bo=
ard members and agreed to rescind the package, once valued as much as $55.8=
 billion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes: Giving $46 billion of stock to Elon Musk =
really would dilute the other shareholders. That=E2=80=99s just true. When =
Tesla initially proposed the pay package in 2018, the tradeoff was =E2=80=
=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll give him $56 billion of stock if he increases the value of=
 the company by $600 billion,=E2=80=9D which was probably a good deal prosp=
ectively. (Shareholders thought so, though Glass Lewis recommended against =
it at the time.) But now that increase in valuation has=C2=A0<em>already ha=
ppened</em>,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> so=C2=A0the judge=E2=80=99s ruling gives Tesla shareholders the chance=
 to get it for free. Musk did all the work already, and they don=E2=80=99t =
have to pay him for it! As a strict economic calculation, maybe they should=
 keep the money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, that does seem unfair, whic=
h probably will motivate some institutional shareholders to vote to give hi=
m the money. But the bigger problem is that if you really do take away this=
 money, that will=C2=A0<em>definitely=C2=A0</em>demotivate him. If Tesla=E2=
=80=99s shareholders vote not to give Musk the bag of money that he wants, =
he will sulk, and his sulking will probably involve working 168-hour weeks =
at several of his many other companies. Back in January =E2=80=94=C2=A0befo=
re his pay package was overturned =E2=80=94 he was <a href=3D"https://link.=
