<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Probably=C2=A0</em>the story of meme stock=
s goes something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because of social media, retail inves=
tors are more able to coordinate with each other to all buy the same stock=
=C2=A0at the same time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because it=
 is fun and occasionally lucrative, they do.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">Some structural feature of the modern stock market gives them=C2=
=A0<em>leverage</em>. The story is not=C2=A0<em>just </em>=E2=80=9Cwhen a l=
ot of retail investors buy a stock at once, it goes up=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=
=99s =E2=80=9Cwhen a lot of retail investors buy a stock at once,=C2=A0<em>=
that causes big institutional traders to buy the stock too</em>, so it goes=
 up.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Steps 1 and 2 of that story are surely true, a=
nd=C2=A0<em>possibly=C2=A0</em>sufficient to explain a lot of meme-stock ac=
tivity.=C2=A0Step 3 is a bit murkier, and not absolutely necessary; it is i=
maginable that, if enough individuals on Reddit buy a stock, the stock will=
 go up a lot. Still most people seem to believe some form of Step 3. The <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35536316.258326/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjUvdGhlLWd=
hbWUtbmV2ZXItc3RvcHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUyOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbW=
FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNTI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB007ab51b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
two main forms are</a>:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The short squeeze: If a lot of retail =
investors buy a stock all at once, its price will go up enough that hedge f=
unds who had=C2=A0<em>shorted=C2=A0</em>the stock will have to get out of t=
heir positions. Those hedge funds will=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>have to buy =
the stock, and then it will really go up a lot.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">The gamma squeeze: If a lot of retail investors buy=C2=A0<em>=
call options=C2=A0</em>on a stock at once, the options market makers who se=
ll them the options will have to buy the underlying stock as a hedge for th=
e call options they sold. This will also push up the stock. And the market =
makers=E2=80=99 hedge is=C2=A0<em>dynamic</em>, meaning that as the stock g=
oes up they have to buy even more stock to remain properly hedged, in a vir=
tuous cycle that further pushes up the stock.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not investment advice, and you should =
not believe these stories <em>too=C2=A0</em>literally; there are no perpetu=
al-motion machines in finance. After the 2021=C2=A0meme-stock mania, the US=
 Securities and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/35536316.258326/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMTkvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1nYW1lc3Rv=
cC1iYWZmbGVzLXRoZS1zZWMtdG9vP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjkyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWR=
pdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDUyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcG=
FpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe9ef1ac5" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
released a report</a> finding some evidence of gamma squeezes and short squ=
eezes, but not really endorsing either theory. And, again, =E2=80=9Ceveryon=
e bought the stock at once=E2=80=9D is at least a theoretically sufficient =
explanation, without any of these technical factors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could also add a third form of retail leve=
rage, which goes something like:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Everyone noticed, in 2021, that retail=
 investors on Reddit could move stocks. So they updated their models, in va=
rious ways, to reflect this. They started paying more attention to social m=
edia, trying to buy stocks that retail investors were talking about. And if=
 they were short sellers, they started paying extra-close attention, so tha=
t they could=C2=A0<em>immediately=C2=A0</em>get out of any short positions =
that looked like they were becoming meme stocks. The result of this is that=
, as soon as retail investors start buying a meme stock, fast-money institu=
tions =E2=80=94=C2=A0momentum-tracking hedge funds, social-media-tracking f=
unds, factor-neutral funds, nervous short sellers =E2=80=94=C2=A0will also =
start buying that stock, and it will go up.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One theory that I have heard about <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35536316.258326/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDUtMTMvZ2FtZXN0b3AtaXMt=
YmFjaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTI5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3V=
yY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MjkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB716a167b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
